We need to prove that the intersection of two binomial random graphs $G_1 \sim \text{Binom}(n, p)$ and $G_2 \sim \text{Binom}(n, q)$ is a binomial random graph $G \sim \text{Binom}(n, p \cdot q)$.

First, let's think about the definition of a binomial random graph. A graph $G \sim \text{Binom}(n, p)$ is constructed by including each edge from the complete graph $K_n$ independently with probability $p$.

Now, consider two binomial random graphs $G_1 \sim \text{Binom}(n, p)$ and $G_2 \sim \text{Binom}(n, q)$. The intersection $G_1 \cap G_2$ is the graph that includes an edge if and only if both $G_1$ and $G_2$ include that edge.

