When we take the intersection `G ⊓ H`, we are considering the graphs that are common to both `G` and `H`. For an edge to be in `G ⊓ H`, it must be in both `G` and `H`. 

Since `G` is binomial with parameter `p`, each edge is in `G` with probability `p`. Similarly, since `H` is binomial with parameter `q`, each edge is in `H` with probability `q`. 

