This lemma shows that the operation of creating a graph from a set of edges is also measurable. 

Now we can define the binomial distribution on graphs. A binomial random graph `G(n, p)` can be defined as the graph obtained by including each possible edge independently with probability `p`. 

In measure theory terms, we can define the probability measure on the space of all graphs (which is isomorphic to the power set of the set of all edges, and thus can be given the sigma-algebra generated by the edge sets).

